ands complicated technology (technical)\n\nCandidate D:\n- Responds to unexpected events adequately (pressure)\n- Can concentrate very well (cognitive)\n- Solves problems extremely well (technical)\n- Takes responsibility seriously (reliability)\n- Considered moody (teamwork)\n- Regarded as a loner (teamwork)\n- No explicit leadership mention\n- No mention of communication\n\nWe need to weigh strengths vs weaknesses for long-distance pilot.\n\nKey criteria: reliability, technical competence, calm under pressure, decision-making, teamwork/communication, professional development.\n\nCandidate A: strong technical and anticipatory skills, leadership, but unfriendly, unorganized, unhealthy habits, poor criticism acceptance. Leadership suggests some teamwork, but unfriendly and unorganized could be problematic for crew cooperation on long flights.\n\nCandidate B: strong conscientiousness, stress handling, weather assessment, computer skills, but nasty remarks, wrong tone, pretentious. Interpersonal issues could affect crew morale. Weak memory for numbers could be safety issue.\n\nCandidate C: quick correct decisions, calm, good attention, concern for others (positive), but difficulty communicating, egocentric, not willing to further education (long-term development). Concern for others may offset communication issues? Egocentric suggests self-centered, contradictory with concern for others. Mixed.\n\nCandidate D: strong problem solving, concentration, responsibility, handles unexpected events, but moody, loner, no leadership, no communication data. Moodiness and loner could affect crew interaction.\n\nWe need to pick best overall. Likely Candidate A's leadership and anticipatory skills are valuable, but unfriendly and unorganized may be serious. Candidate B's interpersonal negatives are strong. Candidate C's communication difficulty is a big issue for crew. Candidate D's moodiness and loner also problematic.\n\nWhich candidate has the best balance? Perhaps Candidate A, despite unfriendly, still has very good leadership and technical skills, and can anticipate danger. Unfriendly may be mitigated by leadership? But leadership requires crew interaction; unfriendly could hinder.\n\nCandidate C has concern for others, calm, quick decisions, but communication difficulty and egocentric may be severe for crew. Not willing to further education is a long-term issue.\n\nCandidate D has strong technical and responsibility, but moody and loner may affect teamwork heavily.\n\nCandidate B has conscientiousness and stress handling, but nasty remarks and tone issues are serious.\n\nThus, maybe Candidate A is still the best overall, as leadership and anticipatory skills are crucial for long-distance flights, and the negatives (unfriendly, unorganized) are less severe than outright communication hostility.\n\nWe should state provisional preference for Candidate A, with uncertainty due to lack of explicit teamwork data. Ask others if they have any positive teamwork info for A or D, etc.\n\nWe need to produce PUBLIC_MESSAGE with reasoning and vote."}
